1
00:00:01,002 --> 00:00:03,204
Okay, so once again, I'm Paulette Vander Kloot.

2
00:00:03,224 --> 00:00:07,307
I'm the facilitator of this subcommittee meeting.

3
00:00:07,407 --> 00:00:14,233
This subcommittee is a subcommittee of the Medford Charter Review Committee.

4
00:00:14,813 --> 00:00:24,982
And the purpose of our particular subcommittee is to consider the organization of the Medford School Committee as it relates to reviewing the charter of the city of Medford.

5
00:00:26,263 --> 00:00:44,239
And so I think this is our third subcommittee meeting and tonight we're going to go over some more interview feedback and we're going to make a list of various pros and cons of the different areas and continue our discussion.

6
00:00:49,023 --> 00:00:59,235
I think we'll begin with the fact that Phyllis Morrison and I went and had a very nice discussion with the mayor.

7
00:00:59,476 --> 00:01:00,357
Did I put that one first?

8
00:01:00,417 --> 00:01:00,677
I did.

9
00:01:01,057 --> 00:01:03,681
With Mayor Brianna Kern, Mungo Kern.

10
00:01:04,942 --> 00:01:06,002
on February 7th.

11
00:01:06,643 --> 00:01:16,670
And I'm going to, I sent out the notes today to the committee members, but since everybody doesn't have them, I'm going to read them into the record.

12
00:01:16,830 --> 00:01:26,877
And Phyllis, then maybe at the end, if you have any other things you wanted to add, Phyllis and I did collaborate this afternoon, so hopefully I've been inclusive.

13
00:01:27,877 --> 00:01:28,698
Just a little background.

14
00:01:28,738 --> 00:01:29,799
Can I ask you a question?

15
00:01:30,259 --> 00:01:30,439
Yeah.

16
00:01:31,100 --> 00:01:31,500
Would it be,

17
00:01:32,723 --> 00:01:37,345
more advantageous to share your screen with the notes and then read them also?

18
00:01:38,785 --> 00:01:40,546
I don't know how to do that, Phyllis.

19
00:01:41,226 --> 00:01:54,130
Actually, Paulette, I put them all in our shared drive, so I could probably, if I can do it right, pull it up from the shared drive.

20
00:01:55,327 --> 00:01:57,749
Okay, so why don't you see if you can do that?

21
00:01:57,789 --> 00:01:58,869
And in the meantime, I'll start.

22
00:01:58,970 --> 00:01:59,530
Is that okay?

23
00:02:00,931 --> 00:02:02,412
Have you made Eunice a co-host?

24
00:02:03,072 --> 00:02:03,393
I have.

25
00:02:03,973 --> 00:02:04,954
Good, then she's okay.

26
00:02:04,974 --> 00:02:06,675
She can share the screen once she gets there.

27
00:02:08,256 --> 00:02:09,397
I can figure out how to do it.

28
00:02:09,797 --> 00:02:11,298
I'll make you a co-host too.

29
00:02:11,778 --> 00:02:12,299
I've got it.

30
00:02:13,474 --> 00:02:19,741
Okay, so Mayor Brianna Lungo-Kern is at the beginning of her third two-year term.

31
00:02:20,381 --> 00:02:23,945
Previously, Brianna served as a member of the Medford City Council.

32
00:02:24,546 --> 00:02:28,970
She was first elected in 2001 and served for 18 years, i.e.

33
00:02:29,090 --> 00:02:32,594
nine terms, before being elected to mayor in 2001.

34
00:02:35,172 --> 00:02:45,001
Mayor Lungo Kern greeted us warmly and extended her thanks and appreciation to the whole Charter Review Committee for undertaking this important initiative.

35
00:02:45,021 --> 00:02:46,762
I'm sorry, Paula.

36
00:02:46,822 --> 00:02:48,724
Can you make me co-host as well?

37
00:02:50,425 --> 00:02:51,006
Is that Aubrey?

38
00:02:52,727 --> 00:02:52,968
Yes.

39
00:02:53,488 --> 00:02:53,828
OK.

40
00:02:54,048 --> 00:02:55,350
I did, and then you went out.

41
00:02:55,950 --> 00:02:56,631
So we'll do it again.

42
00:02:56,791 --> 00:02:57,231
There you go.

43
00:02:58,512 --> 00:02:58,612
OK?

44
00:03:02,378 --> 00:03:05,500
And she greeted us warmly.

45
00:03:05,520 --> 00:03:07,501
There we go.

46
00:03:07,801 --> 00:03:14,204
Now, the funny enough thing is I can't read that at all, so I will continue to read off my paper.

47
00:03:14,364 --> 00:03:15,225
Aubrey, you have it up?

48
00:03:16,327 --> 00:03:16,967
Yes, she does.

49
00:03:17,508 --> 00:03:18,208
Okay, never mind.

50
00:03:19,368 --> 00:03:19,769
That's better.

51
00:03:19,809 --> 00:03:22,730
We began our conversation with the question of term limits.

52
00:03:23,230 --> 00:03:32,515
Brianna told us she had reviewed the tape of the previous Charter Committee meeting and was happy to see that the committee had voted to recommend term limits for the mayor.

53
00:03:33,235 --> 00:03:36,917
She said she would have been happy with either a 12 or 16-year mandate.

54
00:03:37,617 --> 00:03:45,541
Her preference for term limits for the mayor's position comes from her frustration in earlier years with the then long-serving mayor.

55
00:03:46,570 --> 00:03:55,973
We went on to discuss the term length, and the mayor expressed a favorable opinion regarding the suggestion of a four-year length of term for the mayor's position.

56
00:03:56,794 --> 00:04:01,095
It's hard to get a lot done in two years, and the election cycle takes a lot of time and energy.

57
00:04:01,896 --> 00:04:07,538
Brianna is a little uncertain how a four-year term would feel, but believes a longer term would be beneficial.

58
00:04:08,483 --> 00:04:18,692
As we discussed the various pros and cons, the mayor strongly expressed support for the idea of three-year terms for all office holders.

59
00:04:19,453 --> 00:04:21,955
Could three-year terms be possible in Medford?

60
00:04:22,596 --> 00:04:29,842
While she did not know the answer, the mayor hoped our committee would further explore this to see if it would be a possibility.

61
00:04:30,703 --> 00:04:36,849
If the mayor's term was three years, she suggested that the term limit might be 15 years.

62
00:04:37,449 --> 00:04:42,554
Brianna was undecided about term limits for both city council and school committee members.

63
00:04:43,675 --> 00:04:47,698
We discussed ward versus at-large representation for the school committee.

64
00:04:48,399 --> 00:04:51,342
Some combination might be preferable in ward

65
00:04:52,825 --> 00:04:58,108
if wards could be combined and then additional at-large members elected as well.

66
00:04:58,828 --> 00:05:01,230
The size of the committee is a consideration.

67
00:05:01,850 --> 00:05:05,552
Could meetings become less effective with too many members vying to speak?

68
00:05:06,433 --> 00:05:13,377
The mayor reminded us that sometimes it has been challenging to get people to run for school committee due to the large commitment of time.

69
00:05:14,097 --> 00:05:16,762
She wouldn't want to discourage people who are interested.

70
00:05:17,323 --> 00:05:23,995
On the flip side, she understands the drive for possibly being more inclusive by incorporating ward representation.

71
00:05:24,776 --> 00:05:26,499
Would combining wards be a solution?

72
00:05:27,590 --> 00:05:33,934
At first, the mayor admitted it was challenging to work all day and then go on to the school committee meetings.

73
00:05:34,174 --> 00:05:44,121
However, once she got used to it, she enjoys her role and would definitely want to be on the school committee because she is well-versed in the scope of the needs of our students.

74
00:05:44,661 --> 00:05:46,843
Her preference is for the mayor to chair the committee.

75
00:05:48,030 --> 00:05:48,830
balance of power.

76
00:05:49,490 --> 00:05:55,031
And this was really outside of the school committee issue, but she discussed this, so I wanted to include it.

77
00:05:55,831 --> 00:06:05,153
The mayor and several city councilors have been working together to come up with a budget ordinance, which would provide to the city council quarterly budget documentation.

78
00:06:05,833 --> 00:06:14,955
The mayor sees this joint agreement as a positive step in trying to set a more positive tone between the council and the mayor's office.

79
00:06:16,522 --> 00:06:21,664
Okay, so that's really kind of the summation of our meeting with the mayor.

80
00:06:22,204 --> 00:06:23,864
Phyllis, did you want to add anything else?

81
00:06:24,645 --> 00:06:31,787
No, I think as you and I talked, you know, after the meeting and other times, I think that that really encapsulates everything she said.

82
00:06:32,247 --> 00:06:39,469
I would like to say that she was very almost excited as we were at one of our last meetings about the possibility of a three-year term.

83
00:06:39,529 --> 00:06:40,810
I think that's a pretty clear

84
00:06:44,787 --> 00:06:52,369
point of view for a lot of us because the two-year terms are too short because you have to run every, I don't know, can it be possible?

85
00:06:52,449 --> 00:06:54,870
Even the mayor's not sure about that, but she did.

86
00:06:54,970 --> 00:07:04,532
One of the things I do want to share is that when we talked about three limits, you know, one of the questions that keeps coming up, will that be a presidential year, will it be a NAFTA year, be it this year?

87
00:07:04,992 --> 00:07:08,013
But the other point is that she, you know, you know,

88
00:07:08,601 --> 00:07:10,222
we can vote whenever we need to vote.

89
00:07:10,622 --> 00:07:12,263
We have to look at what's best for the city.

90
00:07:12,643 --> 00:07:21,548
And it's nice to know that all of these things are being talked about and discussed so we can get this charter to be most effective for our citizens.

91
00:07:22,874 --> 00:07:23,034
Right.

92
00:07:23,094 --> 00:07:37,623
I think my my takeaway was along the same lines is that in some ways, you know, I've heard this three year I've thought about the three year I've said to myself, oh, if only we could have three year terms and then sort of feeling like, oh, but it's probably impossible.

93
00:07:37,683 --> 00:07:40,985
And there's an inequity between the election cycles.

94
00:07:41,025 --> 00:07:46,148
But one of the things that Brianna says is it would be everybody would be having the same inequity.

95
00:07:46,708 --> 00:07:46,888
Right.

96
00:07:47,108 --> 00:07:51,152
So so she certainly encouraged us to look deeper and further.

97
00:07:51,672 --> 00:08:01,320
And, you know, I don't really personally care if Medford is the only city in the Commonwealth who might say, hey, three years is the right length of term.

98
00:08:02,640 --> 00:08:07,281
You know, and there are some others, they tend to be towns, they tend to have spring elections.

99
00:08:07,901 --> 00:08:12,902
So we certainly, you know, it's really an area of discovery.

100
00:08:13,902 --> 00:08:16,923
But anyway, I thought it was a very nice conversation.

101
00:08:17,623 --> 00:08:26,305
And it was very exciting to talk to her and have her reflect on both the past and the future.

102
00:08:27,946 --> 00:08:29,468
So that's that.

103
00:08:30,008 --> 00:08:32,711
On a personal note for me, it cleared up a lot of things.

104
00:08:33,352 --> 00:08:43,864
As someone who doesn't know that much about the school committee in Medfit, it was nice to talk to Maren, get her understanding and her information that she shared about the school committee with me also.

105
00:08:45,201 --> 00:08:48,061
It was a very, very valuable interview for lots of reasons.

106
00:08:48,602 --> 00:09:03,804
I think that she definitely felt like being on the school committee afforded her the opportunity to know more in depth about the school issues and that that was very, very important for her.

107
00:09:04,344 --> 00:09:05,024
Very important.

108
00:09:05,284 --> 00:09:06,005
Very important.

109
00:09:06,065 --> 00:09:06,245
Yeah.

110
00:09:06,925 --> 00:09:07,245
Okay.

111
00:09:07,705 --> 00:09:07,965
Okay.

112
00:09:08,185 --> 00:09:13,486
Any questions about that interview or about our impressions of the interview?

113
00:09:14,346 --> 00:09:15,227
Aubrey or Eunice?

114
00:09:16,268 --> 00:09:18,911
One question, one thing that stood out to me, a couple of things.

115
00:09:18,971 --> 00:09:29,022
First of all, I'm really glad that you were able to do that because I know she was interviewed with regards to the entire charter and her role as mayor.

116
00:09:29,763 --> 00:09:40,329
You know, the, the, the entire scope, but I think honing in right on the school committee, I think was I'm really glad that we were able to get that done with her.

117
00:09:40,470 --> 00:09:43,031
So, thanks to both of you for for that.

118
00:09:43,091 --> 00:09:45,272
I think it was an important perspective.

119
00:09:45,292 --> 00:09:49,735
1 thing that struck me.

120
00:09:51,945 --> 00:09:59,971
you know, is, she said, you know, getting people to run for school committee is hard because of the time commitment.

121
00:10:00,371 --> 00:10:04,414
And I do remember a year, oh, I don't know, was it five or six elections ago?

122
00:10:04,434 --> 00:10:12,860
Paula, you'll, you know, you're nodding, where nobody ran except for the six incumbents.

123
00:10:13,180 --> 00:10:14,061
Right.

124
00:10:14,101 --> 00:10:20,826
So my question would be is, is the time commitment for the school committee that much different than city council?

125
00:10:24,025 --> 00:10:27,946
The time commitment for school committee is intense.

126
00:10:28,766 --> 00:10:37,709
And you see people perceive that the school committee meets less because they have just two public meetings a month.

127
00:10:38,710 --> 00:10:47,153
Just the two formal, while city council meets every Tuesday and school committee meets every Tuesday.

128
00:10:48,213 --> 00:10:50,015
every other, twice a month.

129
00:10:50,455 --> 00:10:54,418
So it seems like, oh, well, they have two less, but the amount of subcommittee meetings we have.

130
00:10:55,559 --> 00:11:09,230
And I mean, so this past weekend, I saw a bunch of the new school committee members at the Medford Family Network Valentine's Day event.

131
00:11:09,910 --> 00:11:15,515
And as is the tradition, the elected officials are asked to come and scoop ice cream.

132
00:11:16,403 --> 00:11:20,105
And I looked at the new school committee members, and I said, well, how are you doing?

133
00:11:21,105 --> 00:11:27,027
It was almost like there were deers in the headlights with their eyes circling around like a cartoon character.

134
00:11:27,567 --> 00:11:38,112
And I know that Erica had put out saying, well, I've just spent, this is the end of my 40th hour working on school committee things this month.

135
00:11:38,212 --> 00:11:41,913
Now, of course, she's new, and there's an awful lot.

136
00:11:45,073 --> 00:11:54,019
Each one of them, in some way or another, expressed to me of saying that it was a lot to start out with.

137
00:11:54,439 --> 00:11:56,060
It was very, very time consuming.

138
00:11:56,101 --> 00:12:05,567
I see that Nicole Branley, another one of our new school committee members, has just arrived on scene, and she can probably attest to this, but it's a lot.

139
00:12:11,134 --> 00:12:11,874
I had, yes.

140
00:12:12,174 --> 00:12:13,034
Nicole, is that you?

141
00:12:13,634 --> 00:12:15,495
It is, honey.

142
00:12:15,535 --> 00:12:17,656
So am I portraying you accurately?

143
00:12:18,536 --> 00:12:20,737
No, I think that was quite a good interpretation.

144
00:12:20,777 --> 00:12:21,157
Thank you.

145
00:12:23,358 --> 00:12:28,459
So anyway, so a lot of what the school committee does is not really understood.

146
00:12:30,180 --> 00:12:36,762
There were times many, many, many weeks when four out of five nights I was out doing school committee work.

147
00:12:37,262 --> 00:12:38,083
And that might be

148
00:12:38,963 --> 00:12:42,845
going to a student production, going to a subcommittee meeting.

149
00:12:44,265 --> 00:12:51,749
Nicole and I talked the other day, and she was saying, whoa, there are six subcommittees, and I have to head one of them, and I'm on two other ones.

150
00:12:52,269 --> 00:12:53,529
And how do I do?

151
00:12:54,130 --> 00:12:55,830
So it is a lot.

152
00:12:57,371 --> 00:13:05,515
And when I've tried to encourage other people to run for school committee, sometimes they've looked at me basically and said, do you think I'm crazy?

153
00:13:10,459 --> 00:13:17,822
So I just don't want anybody to underestimate the time commitment of school committee members.

154
00:13:17,902 --> 00:13:22,444
To our guests, Nia, I was on the school committee, as you can probably tell.

155
00:13:24,125 --> 00:13:28,287
So anyway, okay, as we move on.

156
00:13:30,073 --> 00:13:32,314
Eunice, you had asked that question about the time commitment.

157
00:13:33,654 --> 00:13:36,095
In my 32 years, there was only one.

158
00:13:36,195 --> 00:13:37,636
So that was 16 elections.

159
00:13:38,136 --> 00:13:40,677
Only one out of 16 had nobody running.

160
00:13:41,257 --> 00:13:49,540
On the other hand, I do know that there were times, including where we really sort of had to drum up interest in running for school committee.

161
00:13:49,900 --> 00:13:57,663
And that's not been unusual that there are times when, you know, in the end, people end up committing, but sometimes

162
00:13:58,803 --> 00:14:00,865
seems a few months ahead of time that there isn't.

163
00:14:00,885 --> 00:14:02,447
Depends.

164
00:14:03,828 --> 00:14:04,709
Eunice, any other thing?

165
00:14:04,909 --> 00:14:05,710
Or Aubrey?

166
00:14:07,071 --> 00:14:12,836
I think that's it for now until we get to, you know, the larger discussions.

167
00:14:13,557 --> 00:14:13,857
Okay.

168
00:14:14,438 --> 00:14:23,326
So next- My only question was about Brianna's suggestion about combining words, but I can save all those kinds of questions for when we have that conversation.

169
00:14:24,246 --> 00:14:24,426
Right.

170
00:14:24,587 --> 00:14:35,042
I thought when we did the pros and cons that we document that I'm suggesting that that's exactly where we're going to put those things in.

171
00:14:35,663 --> 00:14:35,763
OK.

172
00:14:37,298 --> 00:14:38,839
That was my vision, so to speak.

173
00:14:39,979 --> 00:14:45,721
Next interview, which was an interview that I did with former school superintendent Roy Belson.

174
00:14:47,682 --> 00:14:53,705
He and I sat down and chatted for quite a while just for some background information.

175
00:14:54,445 --> 00:15:03,409
Roy Belson served as the superintendent of the Medford Public Schools from 1995 to 2018, one of the longest serving superintendents in Massachusetts.

176
00:15:04,149 --> 00:15:11,897
Prior to that, he served initially as a substitute, a teacher, a program administrator, and then worked in central administration.

177
00:15:12,498 --> 00:15:15,421
Roy grew up in Medford and attended the Medford Public Schools.

178
00:15:15,921 --> 00:15:20,086
He continues to live in Medford with his wife, Maxine, who was a teacher.

179
00:15:20,626 --> 00:15:24,751
Roy remains interested and involved in educational matters across the state.

180
00:15:25,985 --> 00:15:30,709
So the first thing we discussed was really the role of the mayor on the school committee.

181
00:15:31,910 --> 00:15:37,434
And Roy gave some background information, which may or may not.

182
00:15:37,494 --> 00:15:42,558
There's one key piece which sort of explains why he feels so strongly.

183
00:15:43,298 --> 00:15:48,927
So back in the days with ed reform in 1993, the role of the school committee became more established.

184
00:15:49,447 --> 00:15:52,532
School committee was responsible for policy.

185
00:15:52,752 --> 00:15:58,841
Administration was responsible for operations and personnel, with just a few exceptions.

186
00:15:59,938 --> 00:16:08,583
Prior to that, in 1982, Proposition 2 1⁄2 took effect, which meant that the school committee no longer had fiscal autonomy.

187
00:16:09,164 --> 00:16:18,770
Instead, the chief executive officer, who at that time was a city manager, would set the bottom line for the school committee, subject to the approval of the city council.

188
00:16:19,570 --> 00:16:26,954
The city council could cut the bottom line of the school budget, but not add to the school budget, and that continues to this day.

189
00:16:27,935 --> 00:16:30,616
Prior to that, the school committee set their budget number.

190
00:16:31,456 --> 00:16:53,380
The first year that two and a half goes into effect, the then city manager cut the school budget substantially by $3.2 million, which would be equivalent to maybe $10 million today, but cut the school department, but not the city side.

191
00:16:54,260 --> 00:17:02,192
This had an incredible impact on the Medford public schools for years with a huge number of teacher cuts.

192
00:17:03,402 --> 00:17:04,763
Fast forward to today.

193
00:17:05,724 --> 00:17:19,199
If the mayor doesn't have a real stake in the school system, which is developed by the mayor's participation at school committee meetings, he feels it's easier for the mayor not to appreciate all the needs of the school system.

194
00:17:19,980 --> 00:17:24,124
The mayor's attendance puts the mayor in a public setting twice monthly.

195
00:17:25,145 --> 00:17:26,285
In other words, accessible.

196
00:17:26,946 --> 00:17:33,647
It's really important for the person who ultimately makes budget decisions to be involved, as involved as possible.

197
00:17:34,548 --> 00:17:37,429
Roy thinks that the mayor has a citywide perspective.

198
00:17:38,109 --> 00:17:42,010
As the chair, the mayor is able to listen to all the comments from members.

199
00:17:42,650 --> 00:17:45,611
As just one of seven, the mayor is not as accountable

200
00:17:46,884 --> 00:17:47,585
in his opinion.

201
00:17:48,045 --> 00:17:54,269
Also, mayor has a specific role in capital funding proposals, which includes bonding.

202
00:17:55,590 --> 00:18:02,895
Also, some school costs and city services, such as health care, trash, et cetera, are funded on the city side.

203
00:18:03,335 --> 00:18:09,520
And it's vital that the mayor has a full appreciation of school system needs from the municipal side of government.

204
00:18:10,360 --> 00:18:16,084
The school, and now I put this as a direct quote, the school system budget is the largest single budget in the city.

205
00:18:16,504 --> 00:18:19,606
So it's vitally important that the mayor be directly involved.

206
00:18:23,462 --> 00:18:26,383
Next one, ward or at large.

207
00:18:27,324 --> 00:18:30,045
Key to this is how large should the committee be?

208
00:18:30,745 --> 00:18:37,008
More members increases the likelihood for longer meetings and possibly greater dissonance.

209
00:18:37,769 --> 00:18:39,349
Every member needs to be heard.

210
00:18:39,990 --> 00:18:42,191
If ward representation is desired,

211
00:18:42,731 --> 00:18:55,055
then maybe combining two wards for the purposes of electing more localized school committee members would make more sense and still allow for some at-large candidates to provide an overall experience for the city.

212
00:18:56,055 --> 00:19:01,117
